        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-08-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-08-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="342"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d342">
                <head>342. Information Memorandum From the Deputy Assistant Secretary of State for
                    Near Eastern and South Asian Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_VC1" type="from">Van
                        Hollen</persName>) to Acting Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_JUA1"
                        type="to">Johnson</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d342fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, <gloss target="#t_NEA1">NEA</gloss>
                        Files: Lot 73 D 69, Memoranda to the Secretary, July to Aug 1971.
                        Confidential. Drafted in <gloss target="#t_NEAPAF1">NEA/PAF</gloss> by
                        Robert A. Flaten, and cleared by <persName corresp="#p_LLB1"
                            >Laingen</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_VC1">Van
                        Hollen</persName>. On August 9 <persName corresp="#p_ETLJ1">Eliot</persName>
                        sent a copy of this memorandum to <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                            >Kissinger</persName>. (Ibid., <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59,
                        Central Files 1970–73, SOC 10 AFG)</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d342fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_VC1">Van Hollen</persName> briefed <persName
                            corresp="#p_JUA1">Johnson</persName> on the severe impact of drought on
                        Afghanistan. The sale of 100,000 tons of wheat under <gloss target="#t_PL1"
                            >PL</gloss>–480 had been approved recently, and <persName
                            corresp="#p_VC1">Van Hollen</persName> alerted <persName
                            corresp="#p_JUA1">Johnson</persName> that the U.S. could expect an
                        Afghan request for an additional 100,000 tons.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1971-08-09"
                        >August 9, 1971</date>
                </dateline>
                <pb facs="d342-01" n="1" xml:id="d342-01"/>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="underline">Drought in Afghanistan</hi>
                </p>
                <p>For the second straight year, Afghanistan is faced with a drought which is
                    expected to reduce the wheat crop by up to 25 percent and cause the death of up
                    to 70 percent of the livestock (100 percent in some areas). Since wheat is the
                    basic food in the near subsistence, predominantly agricultural economy of
                    Afghanistan, and the pelts from the Karakul sheep, the largest hard currency
                    earning export of Afghanistan, the drought is considered a major national
                    disaster.</p>
                <p>On August 7, Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_NRG1">Neumann</persName> determined
                    that a disaster of the magnitude to require outside assistance exists in
                    Afghanistan. Under standing emergency authority, he is purchasing small amounts
                    of animal feed and heavy lift pumps in Pakistan. If these can be used
                    effectively in Afghanistan, the Ambassador expects to request additional funding
                    for greater quantities.</p>
                <p>On the basis of earlier information on the drought and a preliminary request from
                    the Government of Afghanistan, we have approved the sale of 100,000 tons of
                    wheat to Afghanistan under <gloss target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss>–480 Title I.
                    Negotiations should begin this week, and be concluded promptly. Ambassador
                        <persName corresp="#p_NRG1">Neumann</persName> anticipates a future request
                    for 100,000 tons of Wheat on a grant basis. Since such a request cannot be met
                    under present <gloss target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss>–480 Title II ceilings,
                    Congressional action might become necessary.</p>
            </div>
